{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930111901/0875.xml":{"full_text":"24\nFinancial Market News, Stocks, Bonds, Commodities and Comment\nLISSffIK\nOF MIRKEI\nstressed\nCopper Outlook Looks Bad, Ex*\npert Declares, Explaining It\nIs Due to Shoving Up Prices\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nThe market gave a color\nless performance yesterday.\nStocks dillied and dallied\nmost of the session and\nturned up before the close.\nGenerally the action of the\nmarket was encouraging to\nthe bull forces, as it showed\ngood resistance to continued\nbad news, but there is ob\nviously no rush to buy stocks\nand this in itself is a bar\nrier to any sizeable advance.\nCopper Looks Bad\nWith copper reported offered\nat 11 cents a pound, as against\nthe price of 12 cents established\na few days ago by leading pro\nducers following the worldwide\ncurtailment agreement, the out\nlook for the copper companies\nlooks less promising. As stated\nhere when the price was rushed\nup, the important thing Is whether\nproducers can get any real busi\nness at higher figures and not\nthe price itself. Low rate of\nindustrial activity and the hugh\nsurplus stocks are the two big\ndrawbacks. I can\u2019t see making\nany new commitments in the\ncopper stocks for the present.\nI understand Standard Oil of\nNew Jersey will a \u201cdis\nappointing\u201d earning report for\nthe year. Net in 1929 was $4.75\na share. Prices of crude oil and\ngasoline have been generally bad\nthis year, naturally affecting\nprofits. _____\nWhy Rubber Rose\nRubbers gave the market a lit\ntle fillip by staging a smart ad\nvance with Goodyear, Goodrich\nand the U. S. Rubber issues\nsetting the pace. Rumors that\ncrude rubber would be advanced\nbefore long, as stated here in the\nIsat two days, was responsible\nfor the spurt. The rubbers\nshould work higher and if you\nbought them for the long pull\nforget about them. Earnings\nought to be better next year and\nbig stocks of crude rubber\nbought by the companies at rock\nbottom prices will help. How\never, those who trade from day\nto day would do well to take\nprofits on any further advance.\nBuying of United Aircraft is\nbetter than the selling so don\u2019t\nbe misled by the stock\u2019s recent\nweakness. United will be taken\nsteadily on a scale from 25 by\nInterests Close to the company,\nbut there will be no effort to\nhold the stock up. The company\nhas done well in a bad year. It\nhas magnificent properties and\nlong pull prospects are excellent.\nFarm Stocks Lower\nBreak in the Oliver Farm\nIssues was a reflection of the re\nport that it\u2019s receivables and\nInventories are high and it\u2019s cash\nlow. Current price of the prior\npreferred, which is selling on a\n30 per cent basis, would indicate,\nthe dividend is doomed.\nOliver\u2019s financial position sug\ngests that other agricultural\nequipment companies are in\nsomewhat the same boat as far\nas money outstanding and collec\ntions are concerned, and it is ex\npected that some of them may\nbe forced to do some financing\nbefore long to tide them over un\nless the agricultural situation\nturns for better. It would 1 e\nwell to defer new commitments\nin these stocks for a while.\nRenewed bear pressure on the\nmarket will very likely be directed\nfirst at the rails and the utili\nties. The former\u2019s earnings are\ngenerally bad this year and many\nof the utilities are still selling\nat a high ratio to earnings. The\nsteel stocks probably will be hit.\ntoo, as profits for this quarter\nseem certain to be the worst of\nthe year.\nMove Manipulated\nThe move in Savage Arms looks\ntoo obviously manipulated to be\nfollowed. Action of American\nTelephone indicates that it is\nmeeting a lot of selling and Con\nsolidated Gas, too. Sinclair di\nrectors will cut the dividend to\n$1 on Monday. I understand. The\ncompany probably won\u2019t earn it\nper share this year but it has\noodles of cash.\nI shouldn\u2019t be surprised to see\nloans down again tomorrow de\nspite the higher range of prices\nin the week covered by the re\nport. The rally absorbed a lot\nOs necessitious liquidation. Bohn\nAluminum and Brass should be\nAvoided.\nAuburn is going ahead too fast.\nI like the stock and expect\neventually to see it much higher.\nHowever, I see no reason for its\nrunning away from the parade\nat this early stage. I hear the\ndu Fonts have been steadily pick\ning up the U. 8. Rubber issues\non a scale down. The bear\ncrowd has been selling General\nMoton, g\nWall Street\nHears:\nThat Youngstown Sheet A\nTube (YB) is being bought\nquietly.\nThat Consolidated Gas (G)\nis looked upon as being one of\nthe logical leaders in the utili\nties.\nThat Air Reduction (ADN) is\nan attractive trading purchase\naround $97.\nThat the steels and oils have\nrecovered too rapidly.\n111 ft\nNET RISES\nBROOKLYN MANHATTAN\nTRANSIT SYSTEM Four\nmonths ended October 31 net in\ncome $2,280/119 equivalent after\npreferred dividends to $2.31 a\nshare on 769,911 shares of com\nmon stock against $2,007,933 or\n$1.96 a share in the like 1929\nperiod. Gross for the period\ntotaled $19,612,226. against $20,-\n223,779 last year. October net in\ncome was $667,347, against $630,-\n827 in October, 1929. Gross for\nthe month amounted to $5,036,-\n775, against $5,170,393 in the like\n1928 month.\nCUNEO PRESS, INC.\u2014Nine\nmonths ended September 30, net\nincome $1,059,867 or $5.48 a\nshare in the like 1929 period.\nKINNER AIRPLANE MOTOR\nCORP.\u2014Nine months ended Sep\ntember 30, net operating deficit\n$101,313, against a deficit of $2,-\n244 in the like 1929 period.\nDETROIT EDISON CO.\u2014Ten\nmonths ended October 31, net in\ncome $11,324,122, against $12,454,-\n256 in the like 1929 period.\nMARKET ST. RWY.\u2014Ten\nmonths ended September 30 net\nearnings $1,408,524, against sl,-\n458,203 in the like 1929 period.\nBLACKSTONE VALLEY GAS\nELEC. \u2014September net income\n$202,546; against $220,848 in Sep\ntember, 1929. Twelve months\nended, September 30 net income\n$1,988,943, against $2,070,733 in\nthe preceding 12 months.\nSO\u2019WESTERN GAS &ELEC.\u2014\nQuarter ended September 30 net\nincome $447,874, against $425,173\nin the like 1929 quarter. Twelve\nmonths ended September 30 net\nincome $1,465,120, against $1,517,-\n693 in the preceding 12 months.\nIOWA PUBLIC SER.\u2014October\nnet earnings $148,213 against\n$148,816 in October, 1929. Twelve\nmonths ended October 31 balance\n$778,531 against $738,753 in the\npreceding 12 months.\nYORK RWYS.\u2014Quarter ended\nSeptember 30, net income $183,-\n159 against $173,244 in the like\n1929 quarter.- Twelve months\nended September 30, net income\n$949,590, against $946,515 in the\npreceding 12 months.\nNORTHERN TEXAS ELEC.\u2014\nSeptember net Income $31,006,\nagainst $67,820 in September,\n1929. Twelve months ended Sep\ntember 30, net income $254,825,\nagainst $378,916 in the preceding\n12 months.\nARIZONA EDISON CO.\u2014Nine\nmonths ended September 30, net\nincome $783,432, against $781,429\nin the like 1929 period.\nSales of Pig Iron\nIn N. Y, Improve\nNEW YORK, Nov. 19. \u2014Sales\nof pig iron in the New York dis\ntrict last week were the best in\nsome time, amounting to between\n11,000 and 12,000 tons.\nInquiries outstanding remain\nfairly good, at 5,000 to 6,000 tons,\nand it is understood that there\nis sentiment in the local mar\nket that the current rate of ac\ntivity will be maintained for a\nweek or so at least. There is\nmore active inquiry in other sec\ntions also, it is reported.\nHarriman Explains\nSmall Lot Rates\nIn connection with the recent\nannouncement of Harriman\nCo. that commission charges\nare the regular charges of\nthe stock exchange, it was\nstated yesterday that the same\nrate of commission applies to\nthe purchase or sale of small\nlots with a minimum of $1 on\nthe New York Stock Exchange\nand $2 on the New York Curb.\n$248,000 Dresden\nBonds Called In\nSpeyer Co. as fiscal agents\nhave purchased for cancellation\nthrough the sinking fund $248,000\nbonds of the City of Dresden\n20-year 7 per cent external loan\nof 1925. This represents the\n1930 sinking fund instalment,\nTOTAL SALES\nNEW YORK, Nov. 15 (IJJJB.).\nSales of stock on the New York\nStock Exchange today totaled\n1,710,340 shares, including the in\nactives. Bond sales amounted to\n$4,470,000.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 15 (1.N.5.).\nSales of stock on the New York\nCurb Exchange today totaled\n413,200 shares. Bond sales\nto $1,938,000.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nBUSINESSTREND\nSTUDY SHOWN\nIMPORTftNT\nResearch, Especially in This\nPeriod, Shown to Be Doubly\nValuable Due to Shakiness\nBy LEWIS HANEY\n(Director New York Unlvereity Bureau of\nBuaineM Research and Fortner Econo\nmist of Federal Trade Com\nmission 1.\nThat the business outlook is.\nnow of fundamental and immedi\nate importance to the investor,\nshould be constantly kept in\nmind. The stock market can run\naway from business during a wild\nbull period, but in a period of\ndepression it foUows business\nmuch more closely.\nSpeculators are now much more\ncautious. No one need fear that\nthe market is going to run away\nas long as business recession con\ntinues. In 1921, for example the\nmarket did not hit bottom until\nafter commodity prices were def\ninitely on the rise, employment\nwas gaining, and industrial ac\ntivity in general had turned up.\nNo Exception Now\nThe present major worldwide\ndepression is not apt to furnish\nany exception. It thus becomes\ndoubly important to study busi\nness trends. Both as business\nmen and as investors, such trends\nconcern us. Easy money, govern\nment relief measures, etc., will\nnot become effective until general\nbusiness activity picks up. Then\nand not until then, will the\nabundance of money be a help.\nAs yet. there is no clear indica\ntion that business has hit bottom.\nOctober indexes of industrial pro\nduction will show new lows. Em\nployment indexes for that month\ndid so. Commodity prices con\ntinue to decline on average, and\namong basic raw materials each\nweek shows more price declines\nthan advances.\nForecasters Wrong\nIt is perhaps significant that\nthe forecasters who have been\nmost optimistic all year, are pow\npostponing the dates they nave\nfixed for the final recovery. The\nHarvard Economic Society, for\nexample, after stubbornly insist\ning that genera! recovery was\ncoming last spring, now says that\n\"the end of the decline may be\nexpected between February and\nJune, 1931.\u201d x x\nOs course, we must take a\ngrain of salt with the forecasts\nof a prophet who has been so\nwrong in the past, but we may\nwell note the reasons given. The\nHarvard prophets now say: \u201cBusi\nness is now much reduced, but\nneither the statistical evidence\nnor the present economic situation\ngives assurance that it has yet\nreached bottom.\u201d\nThey state that \u201cin the two\ncycles most closely resembling\nthe present, the declining phase\nin business volumes ran 17 and\n20 months. This suggests that\nthe present decline may have\none to four months yet to run.\u201d\nThey add that past attempts to\nstimulate recovery may result in\npostponing recovery.\nNow Facing Facts\nThe Harvard people look for\nlower retail prices. They express\nthe opinion that a further shrink\nage in demand for goods is prob\nable, on account of reduced in\ndividual incomes and foreign\nprosperity.\nIt may seem discouraging to\nfind such optimistic quarters, but\nwe can note that the Harvard\nprofessors are at least facing\nfacts, and so we can tfive mpre\nweight to their opinion* that \u201ca\nlarge drop below present levels\ndoes not appear probable. The\noutlook is for the end of the de\ncline in business during the ear#\npart of 1931, and steady but\ngradual revival for the remainder\nof that year.\u201d\nThis moderately hopeful view\nwarrants hateful consideration.\n0. 5. MAY SEEK\n5500,000,0110\n\nNew financing by the Treasury\non December 15 Is likely to be in\nthe neighborhood of $500,000,000,\nMaturities in the middle of that\nmonth will aggregate $585,866,-\n000, of which $483,341,000 will be\nin Treasury 3% per cent short\nterm certificates and the balance\nin Treasury bills.\nWhile income tax payments for\nthe December quarter will be\nabout $480,000,000. a major part\nof this revenue will go to the gen\neral fund to wipe out the deficit\nwhich has accrued in between the\ntax payment periods. The paper\ndeficit in the Treasury to date is\n$262,321,541. The deficit is un\nusually large at this period of the\ndue to fact that interest on\nTreasury 4% per cent bonds and\nthe Fourth Liberty Loan bonds\ncame due in October, amounting\nto $150,000,000.\nIt is believed that a new issue\nof Treasury certificates will be\noffered in December at a rate of\ninterest approximating the 2% per\ncent borne by the $334,000,000\ncertificate issue offered Septem\nber Is.\nExchange Experts Select\nNew Market Leaders\nBy LESLIE GOULD\nA poll of the stock market\nletter writers and statisticians\u2014\nthe so-called experts of Wall\nStreet\u2014on what stocks they think\nwill show the greatest apprecia\ntion in value over the next two\nyears has just been completed.\nThese men have been following\nevery movement of the* stock\nmarket for years. They spend\ntheir lives bent over the tickers\nand pouring over corporation re\nports. A total of 540 votes as\ncast in the poll for a total of 155*\nindividual stocks.\nStandard Oil Company of New\nJersey received the greatest num\nber of votes, with General Mo\ntors, Loew\u2019s, Inc., United States\nSteel, American Can and United\nAircraft close behind in the race\nfor favorite.\nThe 26 favorites and their vote\nfollows:\nNo. votes\n1. Standard Oil of N. J. 17\n2. General Motors 15\n3. Loew's, Inc 15\n4. U. S. Steel 14\n5. American Can 14\n6. United Aircraft 14\n7. Union Carbide 12\n8. American Tobacco 11\n9. Radio-KeithOhpheum 11\n10. Du Pont 10\n11. General Electric 10\n12. Electric Bond Share.. 10\n13. Electric Power Light.. 10\n14. American Telephone 9\n15. Woolworth 9\n16. National Dairy 9\n17. International Nickel 9\n18. Consolidated Gas of N. Y. 8\n19. Anaconda 7\n20. National Biscuit 7\n21. Columbia Gas 7\n22. Johns-Manville 7\n23. Air Reduction 7\n24. Radio *6\n25. Aluminum 6\n26. International Telephone ..6\nFive Votes for United\nSurprisingly the following\nstocks, all heavily bulled at va\nrious times in the last year only\nreceived five votes each: United\nCorporation, the Morgan utility\nholding company; American\nSmelting, the Guggenheim copper\nstock; Eastman Kodak. General\nFoods, Borden, the big butter and\nmilk company: Westinghouse,\nGeneral Electric\u2019s cooperating ri\nval; Standard Gas, the Moody-\nSeagraves utility, and American\na,nd Foreign, Electric Bond and\nShare\u2019s foreign subsidiary.\nFour votes each were cast for\nJ. I. Case, the volatile farm equip\nment stock; Gulf Oil. the Mellon\nproperty; American Radiator, the\nbuilding and plumbing company\nAIRPLANE STOCK\nIS CHANGED\nLOS ANGELES, Nov. 19.\u2014Let\nters have been mailed to all stock\nholders of Kinner Airplane and\nMotor Corporation, advising them\nto present their old $1 per stock\ncertificates to the Security First\nNational Bank of Los Angeles tor\nconversion into new no par stock\nby November 20, 1930. The ex\nchange will be effected on the\nbasis of one new share for each 10\nold shares held, under terms of\namendments to the articles of in\ncorporation as recently approved\nby the stockholders.\nIn addition to the change in par\nvalue of the stock and change in\nname of the company to Kinner\nAirplane and Motor Corporation,\nLimited, amendments will aUo re\nduce the authorized capitalization\nfrom 2,100,000 shares to 199,934\nshares.\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs A Co.)\nSALES\nWashington Gas ss, $1,0000405.\nWashington Gas 6s B, SSOOO\n105.\nWashington Gas 6s A, sloo@\n102%.\nWashington Railway and Elec\ntric 4s, SI,OOOOBB.\nPotomac Electric 5% per cent\npfd., 10@107, 100107. 200107,\n100107%.\nAfter call\u2014Washington Gas 6s\nA, $1,000102%.\nCapital Traction ss, $7,000@85.\nCapital Traction Company, 50\u00a9\n50, 10@50, 20@50, 20@50,\nUnlisted Department\u2014Chapin-\nSachs 8 per cent pfd., 100105,\n100105.\nRaleigh Hotel Company, 10 @47,\n10047, 10047, 10047, 10@47.\nPublic Utility Bonds B~ld\"| Ask\nAmer Tel- Telga 4% a '33.1102 I\nAmer Tel Tel 4%r '3\u00bb.,|143 1..\nAm Tel Tel C't\u2019l. Tr ss. .|105(4|..\nAnaconda Pot. R R 55,.| 32 I 83\u2019\u2019\nAna Pot Guar 5s I S 3 98\nCAP Tel of Va 6a. JlO2\nCap Traction RR 5s I 84\u201941 85u\u2018\nCity A Surburban 55....... .80\nGeorgetown Gas Ist 104% 1106\nPotomac Elec cons ss, 102(4110384\nPotomac Elee \u00abs 1953 107\nWash Alex A Mt V Ctt... 3 i\n\u2018U\u2019aah Balts AAn 6\u00bb.......... .35 41\u201d\nWaAhinxtan Gas 6s 10414 105 u\nWash Gas 6a series A...... 102% 103%\nWaati. Gss 6s series 8....105 106\nWash Ry A Elec 4s 87(4 88\nMiscellaneous Bonds\nBarber A Ross Inc 6%aJ.| 87 [so\nChevy Chase Club 6%a....|i00 1..\nD C Paper Mfr 6a........1 go 65\u201d\nW M Cold Storage 55..\u2019,.| 95\nWash Cons Title 6s |.....|i66\u201d\nPubHe\nAmer Tel A Tel I**4|\nCapitol Traction Co 49(4 io (4\nWash Gas Lt Co 11\u00bb 125\nN A W Steamboat 210 260\nPot Elec Pow 6s pfd... ,|IOJ% 111\n\u2022Pot Elec Fwr I1\u00bb. pfd,.,.HOT |IM\n\u2022Wash Ry A El c0m....., 400 1.....\nWash Bj A El M }M\nTAd National Daily\nof the Bakers; Vanadium, the\nfast-stepping steel stock which\ngets the bulk of its income from\nsecurities, and the volatile Worth\nington Pump, tool maker and oil\nequipment.\nThree Votes for Central\nThree votes each were placed\non National Power, Electric Bond\nand Share unit; Public Service of\nNew Jersey, which dominates Jer\nsey; New York Central, the old\nwar horse of the railroads; Ameri\ncan Gas, another one of the Elec\ntric Bond and Share group; Mont\ngomery-Wkrd, the mail-order\nhouse; Drug, Inc., owner of the\nLiggett drug stores; Standard\nBrands, the Morgan food com\nbine; Paramount, of movie fame.\nUnited Gas, Electric Bond and\nShare-Moody-Seagraves property;\nAmerican Syanamid, the chemical\nfertilizer company that once\nsought Muscle Shoals; Allied\nChemical, really an investment\ntrust in chemicals; Gold Dust, the\nMorrows food company; Ford,\nLtd., Mr. Ford\u2019s representative in\nthe British field, and Chrysler,\nthe third largest United States\nmaker of autos.\nTwo for United Light\nThe following received two\nvotes: Electric Auto-Lite, United\nLight, the Eaton-Otis, and Com\npany, public utility; American\nInternational, one of the oldest\nof investment trusts; Texas Pa\ncific Land Trust, a royal oil out\nfit with some sulphur properties;\nColumbia Carbon, Gillette Safety\nRazor, Kroger Grocery, the chain\nstore company that had all the\ntrouble within its management\nabout a year ago; Underwood-\nElliott, the typewriter stocks;\nBethlehem Steel, foe of the\nEaton-Otis Interest; Otis Elevator;\nAtlantic Refining, one of the\nStandard Oil units; R. H. Macy.\nInternational Business Ma\nchine, Houston Oil, a leading\nfactor in the natural gas field;\nAmerican Machine and Foundry,\nU. 8. Rubber preferred, Kreuger\nand Toll, the Swedish Match\nTrust Holding Company, North\nAmerican, the public utility that\nhas been paying for several years\nas dividends 10 per cent in stock;\nContinental Can. American Can\u2019s\nrival; Republic Steel, the Eaton-\nOtis steel \u201ctrust\u201d; Best and Com\npany, Safeway Stores, Sears,\nRoebuck, American Water Works,\nPennick and Ford, the syrup\nstock; Mathieson Alkali, chemical\nmaker; A. M. Byers, pipe maker;\nColumbia Graphone, and Auburn,\nthe automobile stock that sold\nabove 500 last year.\nBUILDINGWS\nDEGEINE\nAccording to official reports of\nbuilding permits as issued in 589\ncities and towns and compiled by\nS. W. Straus Co., volume of\npermits issued during October\ntotaled $153,055,932, against $169,-\n375,999 in September, a loss of 10\nper cent, normally an increase of\nabout 5 per cent may be expected\nin October over September.\nIn October, 1929, building per\nmits amounting to $253,680,960\nwere issued October this year,\nthus showing a drop of 40 per\ncent from a year ago.\nIn the group of 25 cities re\nporting largest volume of build\ning permits for October the de\ncline from September was 1 per\ncent, and from October, 1929,\nwas 35 per cent. Ten of these\ncities went ahead of October last\nyear, Straus states.\nLocal Stocks\nI Bid I Auk\nXqtlo\u2014l Bank Stocka\nCapital 230 1250\nColumbia 400\nCommercial (stamped) 223 1235\nDistrict 208 1230\nFederal-American 266 1270\nLiberty 195 !210\nLincoln (400 1425\nMetropolitan ...............1320 >4OO\nRlkirs 1425 1495\nSecond 1175 205\nWashington 1240 250\n1 T r\u00bb\u00bbt Company Stocks I\nAmer. See. A Tr. A Tr. C0..|355 380\nContinental Trust 1120 140\nMeeh Bk A Tr. 1105 113\nNat\u2019l. Sav. A Tr 440 495\nPrince Georges Bk. A Tr.. 28 30\nUnion Trust 225 250\nLoan A Tr. 445 1460\nSavings Baak Stocks I\nBank ot Bethesda I 58 65\nCom A Savings ....1325\nEast Washington 25 35\nPot Savings Bank 65 75\nSec Sav A Com Bank <7l 500\nSeventh Street 305\nUnited States 530 1630\nWash Mechanics 50 I 60\nFire insurance Stocks I I\nAmerican 1-300 1....,\nCorcoran 1150 I\nFiremen's I 30 I 34\nNational Union I 20 -I 26\nTitle Insoraiice Stocks I I\nColumbia .............I 8 11\n1 Real Estate U\u00bb5 1\u2122\nTitle A Inv Co Md com... .1 20 I 30\nMleeellaaeous Stocks I\nBarber A Rocs Inc c0m.... 13 15(4\nChevy Ch Dairy pfd 107 110\nCol-Medical Bldg Corp 100 125\nCol Sand A Grav pfd...... 82 89\nD C Paper Mfg pfd., 10\nDiet Natl Sec pfd 68 75\nEmer Bromo-Sels A........30 33\nFederal Storage Pfd 11# 1\nFed-Am Co com 29% 81\nFed-Am Co pfd..../ 10?\n\u2022Lanston Monotype 102% 10a\nMer Tr A Stge com 107 114\nMer Tr A Strge pfd \u00bb<%l\nMergenthaler Lino 88(4 89(4\nNatl Mtge A Inv pfd 5\nPeoples Drug Strs Pfd 6(4 f\nReal Eat M A G pfd 6% 1\nSecurity Storage 10* H-\nTer Ref A Wh Corp 45 50\nThe Carpel Corp 28%\nW Meeh Mtgo com 8%\nWash Med Bldg C0rp...... 80 1.....\nWdw* LotXfop ptd...... 105 Ul*\nWEDNESDAY\u2014NOVEMBER 19\u20141930\nGOODHUE 5\nRECESSION NOT\nTO LAST EON 6\nPresident of International\nAcceptance Bank Sounds\nNote of Cheer at Parley\nThe great natural resources of\nthe United States, the unbounded\nenergy resourcefulness and the\ngenius of the American people,\ncoupled with their unusually\nhigh standards of living and their\nenormous saving ability, are con\nvincing evidences of the recupera\ntive powers o$ the country and\ninspire confidlhce that the pres\nent depression will not continue\nover a protracted period, F, Ab\nbot Goodhue, president of the\nInternational Acceptance Bank\nand of the American Acceptance\nCouncil, declared last night, in\nNew York.\nMr. Goodhue addressed an\naudience of 500, including many\nbankers, and industrial leaders,\nat the twelfth annual dinner of\nthe Acceptance Council. Eugene\nMeyer, governor of the Federal\nReserve Board was the guest of\nhonor, and Alexander Legge\nchairman of the Federal Farm\nBoard, also spoke, discussing the\nvarious phases of the agricultural\nproblem.\nWorld Wide Unrest\nMr. Goodhue declared:\n\u201cNineteen hundred and thirty,\nwill be written down in this\ncountry as a year of readjust\nment after the unparalleled\nbusiness activity and unbounded\nspeculation of the previous\nyear, as a period marked by a\ndrastic fall of commodity prices,\naccompanied by business hesi\ntancy and recession, unemploy\nment and decreased earnings,\nwith similar conditions prevail\ning throughout the world ag\ngravated by political unrest in\nEurope and revolutions in the\nFar East and Central and\nSouth America.\n\u201cEvery country has its periods\nof over-optimism accompanied\nby excesses which in turn are\nfollowed by readjustments and\nthe usual depressions. These\nchastening conditions are un\ncomfortable but necessary.\n\u201cWith the dynamic potenti\nalities of the United States, we\nrealize that adverse conditions\ncannot remain long and we\nface the future with hope, op\ntimism and confidence, realis\ning that beyond the horizon\nawait better times.\nBanks Unusually Sound\n\u201cThe unusually strong and\nsound condition of the banks\nthroughout the country, which\nare backed by the unparalled\nstrength and resources of the\nFederal Reserve System and its\nintelligent management by able,\nhigh-minded men, warrant our\nfaith that we have a bed-rock\nfoundation upon which we may\ngo ahead and rebuild for the\nfuture.\u201d\nAlexander Legge, discussing the\nfarmer\u2019s problem, declared that\nproduction had been carried on\nblindly in the hope that in some\nway conditions would adjust\nthemselves to the point where he\nwould be able to obtain a better\nreturn for the effort expended.\nOnly through co-operative or\nganizations, Mr. Legge main\ntained, could the essential facts\nbe brought to the attention of\nfarmers and through their own\norganizations could such adjust\nments in proportion as are neces\nsary be made effective.\nS E E HARDWARE\nTRADE GAINING\nNEW YORK, Nov. 19.\u2014Mild\nweather continues to retard the\ndemand for seasonable lines in\nmost of the principal hardware\nmarkets throughout the country,\nHardware Age will say tomorrow\nin its weekly market summary.\nHowever, an accelerated move\nment of holiday merchandise is\nresponsible for an expanded sales\nvolume, although Christmas buy\ning has been affected by general\nbusiness conditions.\nSentiment in the trade is bet\nter than it has been for some\ntime, and it is the consensus of\nopinion that hardware stores will\nreceive their share of the Christ\nmas trade, because of the practi\ncal and useful nature of the ar\nticles they offer for gift purposes.\nEarly indications confirm the\nview, which is justified by the\nfact that the general public may\nbe expected to spend less money\nfor presents classified as luxuries.\nShelf hardware and staple lines\ncontinue to move ip moderate\nvolume. Future orders for spring\ndelivery are being booked In fair\nvolume. A slightly better demand\nexists for builders\u2019 hardware and\ntools.\nLittle fluctuation has occurred\nin prices, although an easier\ntrend continues to prevail. Read\njustments, In scattered instances\nhave been responsible for a few\nrevisions of minor importance.\nThe credit situation to fairly\nsatisfactory.\nUnder Fire 1\n\u2014Time\u00ab Staff Photo\nL. F. LOREE\nRAILROAD. MAGNATE who\nis sponsoring the short line\nroute between New York and\nPittsburgh. This plan has been\natacked by a number of lead\ning railroad men.\nOHIO ELECTRIC\nINCREASES\nOHIO ELECTRIC POWER\u2014\nQuarter ended September 30: Net\nincome, $33,249, against $22,752\nin the like '1929 quarter. Twelve\nmonths ended September 30: Net\nincome, $189,472, against $212,-\n437 in the preceding 12 months.\nMICHIGAN ELECTRIC POWER\n\u2014Quarter ended September 30;\nNet income, $44,972, against $31,-\n336 in the like 1929 quarter.\nTwelve months ended September\n30: Net income, $178,678, against\n$154,891 in the preceding 12\nmonths.\nNORTHWEST UTILITIES\u2014\nQuarter ended September 30:\nNet income, $558,762, against\n$465,937 in the like 1929 quarter.\nTwelve months ended September\n30: Net income, $2,752,741, against\n$2,088,095 in the preceding 12\nmonths.\nSOUTHERN CALIFORNIA\nTELEPHONE\u2014September net in\ncome, $782,565, against $639,506\nin September, 1929. Nine months\nended September 30: Net income,\n$6,220,888, against $6,294,726 in\nthe like 1929 period.\n\u2022NORTH AMERICAN CAR\nCORP.\u2014Nine months ended Sep\ntember 30. net profit $523,554,\nagainst $576,625 in the like 1929\nperiod. Quarter ended September\n30, net profit $175,950, against\n$208,187 in the like 1929 quarter.\nASSOCIATES INVESTMENT\nCO.\u2014Ten months ended October\n31 net profit $844,036 or $9.59 a\nshare, against $834,080 or $9.47 a\nshare in the like 1929 period.\nMICHIGAN STEEL CORP.\u2014\nNine months ended September 30\nnet income $639,530 or $2.66 a\nshare against $1,689,888 or $7.68\na share in the like 1929 period.\nQuarter ended September 30 net\nincome $11,094 or 4 cents a share\nagainst $509,888 or $2.32 a share\nin the like 1929 quarter.\n8 Banks Given Right\nTo Sue in Big Fraud\nALBANY, N, Y\u201e Nov. 19\n(I.N.S.).\u2014Under a decision of the\nCourt of Appeals today six banks\n'in New York city may sue three\nother banks in connection with\nthe financial operations of\nCharles D. Waggoner, now serv\ning a sentence in Atlanta prison\nfor using the mails to defraud.\nThe National City Bank, First\nNational Bank, Harriman Na\ntional Bank and Trust Company,\nChemical Bank and Trust Com\npany and the Guaranty Trust\nCompany are seeking to recover\n$500,000 which it is alleged was\ndiverted by Waggoner to the\nChase National Bank, Central\nHanover Bank and Trust Com\npany and the First National Bank\nof Pueblo. Col.\nWEEKLY SALES\nNEW YORK, Nov. 15 (1.N.5.),\nSales of stock on the New York\nStock Exchange for the week\nended today totaled 18,973,040\nshares, including the inactives.\nBond sales amounted to $56,-\n319,000.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 15 (1J4J3.).\nSales of stock on the New York\nCurb Exchange for the week\nended today totaled 4,575,700\nshares. Bond sales amounted to\n$22,474,000.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main -Office in Washington\nMEMBERS I-.\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\n2 MORE HANKS\nIN KENTUCKY\nARE CLOSED\nTen Institutions Have Shut\nDoors This Week; All Are\nCalled Solvent by Bankers\ni\nLOUISVILLE, Ky\u201e Nov.\u2019 13\n(INB.).\u2014Kentucky banks tha?\nhave closed their doors this week\nnumbered 10 today with suspen\nsion of the Owsley Deposit Bank\nat Booneville, and the Peoples\nBank of Sulphur.*\nIn most instances the suspen\nstons were believed to be only\ntemporary, according to bankers\nwho described the closed insti\ntutions as being solvent.\nFive banks in Louisville, includ\ning the National Bank of\nKentucky and the Louisville\nTrust Company, having total re\nsources of nearly $70,000,000,\nclosed their doors, yet anticipated\nruns have not materialized. De\npositors for the most part took\nthe events with little hysteria,\nbankers said.\nNumber of Closed Arkansas\nBanks Is Now 55\nLITTLE ROCK, Ark., Nov. 19\n(LNJS.).\u2014A total of 55 banking\nhouses were closed today in Ar\n\u2022kansas as the result of two days\nof widespread suspensions.\nThe majority of the houses are\ntaking advantage of the State law\npermitting a temporary five-day\nsuspension of business and will\nreopen at the end of that period,\nbankers said.\nForty-three closed their doors\nMonday and 12 more ceased busi\nness yesterday. Seven of those\nthat closed their doors for the\nfive-day period and the remain\nder announced that they are to\nreorganize.\nUESTnVELDANS\nSNOWDROP\n\nThe Federal Reserve Board\u2019s\ncondition statement of week re\nporting member banks in leading\ncities on November 12 shows' de\ncreases for the week of $76,000.-\n000 in loans and investments,\n$17,000,00 in borrowings from Fed\neral reserve banks and $23,000,000\nin Government deposits, and in\ncreases of $220,000,000 in net de\nmand deposits and $5,000,000 in\ntime deposits.\nLoans on securities declined\n$157,000,000 at reporting banks in\nthe New York district, $10,000,000\neach in the Boston and Chicago\ndistricts, and $181,000,000 at all\nreporting banks. \u201cAll other\u201d loans\nincreased $40,000,000 in the New\nYork district and $8,000,000 in the\nChicago district and declined $13,-\n000,000 in the Boston district, all\nreporting banks showing a net in\ncrease of $42,000,000.\nA Year Ago\nThe stock market staged a\nrally today and prices were up\nfrom 1 to more than 9 points\non heavy buying in the last\nhour.\nSales for the day totaled\n2,746,770 shares and the ticker\nwas right up with the market\nat the dose.\nAir Reduction gained 9%, at\n109%.\nAmerican Can closed at 109%,\nup 7%.\nAmerican Water Works was\nup 8, to 70.\nAuburn Auto closed at 165, up\n9.\nGeneral Electric was up 5, at\nIM.\nWestinghouse Electric closed\nat 125, up\nAmekm Telenme and Telegraph Compact\n165th Dividend\nTub regular quarterly\ndividend of Two Dollars\nand Twenty-Five Cents\n($2.25) per share will be\npaid on January 15, 1931, to stock\nholders of record at the dose of bud\nnets on December 20,1930.. h\nH. BLAIR-SMITH, Treasure*","height":"30391","width":"24252"}}
